	I use both Dos/windows and OS/2 (thank God for boot manager).  I 
have been very impressed with OS/2 while using Os/2 programs but it is 
still not a "better Windows than Windows".  I've been quietly following 
the Chicago(Windows95) vs OS/2 threads and they all revolve around people 
arguing on which is better technically.  In my opinion the real factor 
determining an operating systems success is it's software base; and this 
is where MS dominates.  When windows95 hits the shelf, as buggy as it 
might be, it will probably run windows 3.1 apps better than OS/2 3.0 
(This is just an opinion...don't flame me).  And soon after a ton of 
32bit windows95 apps will hit the stores.  The average consumer (one who 
doesn't know what pre-emptive multitasking or even what 32-bit means) 
will buy Windows95 because they've been using Windows 3.1 and because 
they'll see the 'Windows95 approved' sticker on all the software 
packages.  We can argue endlessly about which OS is superior, but until 
IBM starts seriously marketing OS/2 and major software companies 
start supporting it, OS/2 is doomed to stay at second place.       

-Joe

